Preliminary Wrangling¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others..

pd_list = ['Past Due (1-15 days)','Past Due (16-30 days)','Past Due (31-60 days)','Past Due (61-90 days)', 'Past Due (91-120 days)', 'Past Due (>120 days)']
lr_list = ['Past Due (1-15 days)','Past Due (16-30 days)']
hr_list = ['Past Due (31-60 days)','Past Due (61-90 days)', 'Past Due (91-120 days)', 'Past Due (>120 days)']
curr_list = ['FinalPaymentInProgress','Current']
dc_list = ['Chargedoff','Defaulted' ]
def get_cat(ls):
    if ls in lr_list:
        return 'Low Risk'
    elif ls in hr_list:
        return 'High Risk'
    elif ls in curr_list:
        return 'Current'
    elif ls in dc_list:
        return 'Defaulted/ChargedOff'
    else:
        return ls
df['LStatus']= df.LoanStatus.apply(get_cat)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113937 loans in the dataset with 81 features: bool(3), float64(50), int64(11), object(17).
After cleaning we have 113061 loans with 14 features: bool(2), category(2), float64(4), int64(1), object(4), periodA-DEC.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest are:

  • The loan status to predict which loans are likely to be completed and which are likely to be defaulted.
  • The borrower anual percentage rate (APR) to check what affects this rate.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • I expect borrower monthly income, employment status, occupation, loan amount and term to be the most significant parameters for loan completion. Other factors that may affect the loan status include prosper score, income being verified, monthly loan payment and owning a home.
  • For APR, I expect the prosper score, employment status, monthlt income and its verification to be the most significant parameters, while occupation and owning a home can also affect the rate.
  • The year will also be included in the analysis to detect any trends.

  • For all loan amounts, defaulted loans have higher APR than completed ones.
  • For all loan statuses, the median and quartiles of monthly income are nearly the same, however the distribution of loan amounts differs. The loan amounts of completed and defaulted loans (closed loans) are similarly distributed, while the open loans tend to have more values.
